# TypeScript Standards

## Strict Mode

- `strict: true` in all tsconfigs. No `any` — use `unknown` with type guards.
- Prefer `interface` for object shapes, `type` for unions/intersections/utilities.
- Shared types live in `packages/types/`, never duplicated across apps.

## Naming

- `.ts` files: `kebab-case` (e.g., `chat-service.ts`, `use-chat.ts`, `create-agent.dto.ts`)
- `.tsx` component files: `PascalCase` (e.g., `MessageBubble.tsx`, `AgentCard.tsx`)
- Classes/interfaces: `PascalCase`
- Functions/variables: `camelCase`
- Constants: `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`
- Enums: `PascalCase` name, `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` members (matches Prisma-generated enums)

## Imports

- Use path aliases (`@centrai/types`, `@centrai/ui`, `@/lib`, `@/components`).
- No relative imports that go up more than one level (`../../` max).
- Barrel exports (`index.ts`) in each module/package — import from barrel, not internal files.

## Error Handling

```typescript
// ❌ Silent catch
try { await fetchData(); } catch (e) {}

// ✅ Log + rethrow typed error
try {
  await fetchData();
} catch (error) {
  this.logger.error('Failed to fetch data', { error });
  throw new AppError('DATA_FETCH_FAILED', { cause: error });
}
```

## Functions

- Prefer named exports over default exports.
- Max one class per file. Pure utility functions can share a file.
- Use `readonly` for properties that shouldn't be reassigned.

## Validation

- Use Zod schemas (in `packages/types/`) for runtime validation.
- Derive TypeScript types from Zod with `z.infer<typeof Schema>`.
- Never trust external input — validate at API boundaries.
